Python Syntax Basics ‚Äî File I/O (Input & Output)

File I/O is the backbone of real automation work.
Whether you're cleaning reports, processing church attendance files, exporting CSVs, or uploading logs ‚Äî File I/O is where Python shines.

This page covers reading, writing, appending, working with JSON/CSV, and using pathlib (the modern way).

üìÑ 1. Opening Files

Python uses the open() function.

Basic pattern
file = open("data.txt", "r")
content = file.read()
file.close()


But the right way is using a context manager (with) ‚Äî it closes the file automatically.

Recommended
with open("data.txt", "r") as f:
    content = f.read()

üì• 2. Reading Files
Read the entire file
with open("notes.txt", "r") as f:
    text = f.read()

Read line-by-line
with open("notes.txt", "r") as f:
    for line in f:
        print(line.strip())

Read all lines into a list
with open("notes.txt", "r") as f:
    lines = f.readlines()

üì§ 3. Writing Files
Overwrite (creates file if not exists)
with open("log.txt", "w") as f:
    f.write("Automation started\n")

Append (add to bottom)
with open("log.txt", "a") as f:
    f.write("New entry added\n")

üìù 4. Writing Multiple Lines
lines = ["Item 1\n", "Item 2\n", "Item 3\n"]

with open("list.txt", "w") as f:
    f.writelines(lines)

üîß 5. File Modes
"r"  read
"w"  write (overwrite)
"a"  append
"x"  create file, fail if exists
"rb" read binary
"wb" write binary


Binary mode matters for images, audio files, PDFs, etc.

üü¶ 6. Working with JSON Files

Super useful for configs, reports, or API responses.

Load JSON
import json

with open("data.json") as f:
    data = json.load(f)

Save JSON
with open("data.json", "w") as f:
    json.dump(data, f, indent=4)

üìä 7. Working with CSV Files
Read CSV
import csv

with open("users.csv") as f:
    reader = csv.reader(f)
    for row in reader:
        print(row)

Write CSV
import csv

rows = [
    ["Name", "Age"],
    ["Ron", 41],
]

with open("users.csv", "w", newline="") as f:
    writer = csv.writer(f)
    writer.writerows(rows)

üìÇ 8. Using Pathlib (HIGHLY recommended)

pathlib is more modern and cleaner than os.

Create paths
from pathlib import Path

folder = Path("reports")
file = folder / "summary.txt"

Check if file exists
if file.exists():
    print("Ready to process")

Read text quickly
content = file.read_text()

Write text quickly
file.write_text("Hello, world!")

üîç 9. Listing Files in a Folder
from pathlib import Path

folder = Path("uploads")

for f in folder.glob("*.pdf"):
    print(f)


Patterns you can use:

*.txt
*.csv
**/*.txt      # recursive

üßπ 10. Deleting Files
from pathlib import Path

file = Path("old_file.txt")

if file.exists():
    file.unlink()

üöÄ Real Automation Examples
Auto-clean a folder (delete large files)
from pathlib import Path

folder = Path("videos")

for f in folder.glob("*.mp4"):
    if f.stat().st_size > 50_000_000:
        f.unlink()

Combine multiple CSV files
import csv
from pathlib import Path

folder = Path("reports")
output = []

for f in folder.glob("*.csv"):
    with f.open() as file:
        reader = csv.reader(file)
        output.extend(list(reader))

with open("combined.csv", "w", newline="") as f:
    writer = csv.writer(f)
    writer.writerows(output)

Save API results to a JSON file
import requests
import json

data = requests.get("https://api.example.com/data").json()

with open("api_data.json", "w") as f:
    json.dump(data, f, indent=4)

üìù Quick Reference
open("file.txt", "r")         # read
open("file.txt", "w")         # write
open("file.txt", "a")         # append

file.read()                   # read whole file
file.readlines()              # list of lines

json.load()                   # read JSON
json.dump()                   # write JSON

csv.reader()                  # read CSV
csv.writer()                  # write CSV

Path("folder").glob("*.txt")  # list files
Path("file").unlink()         # delete file
